%h2 Messages

.alert
  %button.close{data: {dismiss: 'alert'}} ×
  <strong>Warning!</strong> Your monthly traffic is reaching limit.
.alert.alert-success
  %button.close{data: {dismiss: 'alert'}} ×
  <strong>Success!</strong> The page has been added.
.alert.alert-info
  %button.close{data: {dismiss: 'alert'}} ×
  <strong>Info!</strong> You have 198 unread messages.
.alert.alert-error
  %button.close{data: {dismiss: 'alert'}} ×
  <strong>Error!</strong> The daily cronjob has failed.


= widget_box title: 'Notifications', icon: 'comment' do
  %p Growl style notifications can be created using gritter.  Just apply a <code>rel="gritter"</code> to an element with a <code>data-message</code> attribute.  Check how we use additional data attributes to specify a few options.
  %button.btn{rel: 'gritter', title: 'Standard', data: {message: 'You can provide simple messages using the data-message attribute.'}} Standard
  %button.btn.btn-warning{rel: 'gritter', title: 'Sticky', data: {message: 'This message is sticky.', sticky: 'true'}} Sticky
  %button.btn.btn-success{rel: 'gritter', title: 'Image', data: {message: 'This includes an image.', image: 'https://en.gravatar.com/userimage/4301562/87d8738abb11e916439334ce8626b4ae.jpeg'}} Image


= widget_box title: 'Modal dialogs', icon: 'comment-alt' do
  %p Modal dialosgs are created by adding a <code>rel="modal"</code> attribute to any element.  It's advised that these go on <code>a</code> tags because there's typically a href associated with it.

  %a.btn.btn-primary{href: '#modal_example', rel: 'modal'} Simple Modal
  #modal_example.modal.hide
    .modal-header
      %button.close{type: 'button', data: {dismiss: 'modal'}} ×
      %h3 Alert modal
    .modal-body
      %p Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet...
    .modal-footer
      %a.btn.btn-primary{href: '#', data: {dismiss: 'modal'}} Confirm
      %a.btn{href: '#', data: {dismiss: 'modal'}} Cancel

  %a.btn.btn-primary{href: adminsimple.root_path, rel: 'modal'} Ajax Modal
